T4_value: Lancewood (Nectandra coriacea), also called black torch, and sweet torchwood, is a tropical tree in the laurel family that grows up to 12 meters (25 feet) tall.  It is native to hardwood hammocks in Florida, central America and Caribbean.  When crushed, the leaves give off a licorice-like smell, and it produces clusters of delicately scented white flowers that attract insect pollinators.  It produces a drupe fruit that resembles a miniature avacado (approximately 1 cm or 0.5 inch long), purple when mature and eventually turns black.
